- A transition matrix is set up so that the columns represent the current state, and the rows represent the future state after one transition. The position of the entry $0.2$, representing the $20\%$ moving from A to B, tells us the order of the columns and rows, as shown:
  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/d40a6ea7-3d5e-40c7-bc0c-472fbaf615c8/images/ddade603-af2f-4448-a257-d11ba83a7fd6/1199b.JPG)


  The entries in each column must add up to $1$, therefore we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &\hspace{-6em}\bm{T} =  \begin{bmatrix*} \answer{0.8} & x \\[4pt] \hspace{0.5em}0.2 & \answer{1-x} \end{bmatrix*} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- To find the eigenvalues of a $2 \times 2$ matrix, we use the formula $|\bm{T} - \lambda I|=0$. Using this formula with $\lambda = 0.5$, we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \Bigg|\begin{bmatrix} 0.8 - 0.5 & x \\[4pt] 0.2 & 1-x-0.5 \end{bmatrix} \Bigg| &= 0 \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[15pt]
  0.3(0.5 - x) - (x)(0.2) &= 0 \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[9pt]
  0.15 - 0.3x - 0.2x &= 0 \\[6pt]
  &\hspace{-0.9em}\tcbhighmath{x = 0.3} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We know that $x=0.3$ and therefore $1-x=0.7$. Our matrix equation for the number of chickens in each coop after $3$ nights is as follows:

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \begin{bmatrix} 0.8 & 0.3 \\[4pt] 0.2 & 0.7 \end{bmatrix}^3 \,\times \, \begin{bmatrix} 30 \\[4pt] 210 \end{bmatrix}  &= \begin{bmatrix} 129.75 \\[4pt] 110.25 \end{bmatrix} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  This shows that after three nights, there are more chickens in coop A than in coop B $(129.75 > 110.25)$. To show that this is the $\textbf{first}$ time that this has occurred, when can compute a similar calculation for the first night and the second night:

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \begin{bmatrix} 0.8 & 0.3 \\[4pt] 0.2 & 0.7 \end{bmatrix}^1 \,\times \, \begin{bmatrix} 30 \\[4pt] 210 \end{bmatrix}  &= \begin{bmatrix} 87 \\[4pt] 153 \end{bmatrix} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[6pt]
  \begin{bmatrix} 0.8 & 0.3 \\[4pt] 0.2 & 0.7 \end{bmatrix}^2 \,\times \, \begin{bmatrix} 30 \\[4pt] 210 \end{bmatrix}  &= \begin{bmatrix} 115.5 \\[4pt] 124.5 \end{bmatrix} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  In both cases we see that the number in coop B is still greater than that in coop A.
  Therefore, it as after $\answer{\text{$3$ nights}}$ that there are first more in coop A than B.

  $$
  \begin{aligned}			
  \tag*{\textbf{AG}}	
  \end{aligned}
  $$

- To find the eigenvectors of the $2 \times 2$ matrix $\bm{T}$, we solve the equation

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \begin{bmatrix} 0.8 - \lambda & 0.3 \\[4pt] 0.2 & 0.7 - \lambda \end{bmatrix} \,\times \, \begin{bmatrix} x \\[4pt] y \end{bmatrix}  &= \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\[4pt] 0 \end{bmatrix}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  using firstly $\lambda_1=0.5$ and secondly $\lambda_2=1$. The values we find for $x$ and $y$ will be the elements of eigenvectors $\bm{p}_1$ and $\bm{p}_2$.
  For $\lambda_1=0.5$, we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \begin{bmatrix} 0.3 & 0.3 \\[4pt] 0.2 & 0.2 \end{bmatrix} \,\times \, \begin{bmatrix} x \\[4pt] y \end{bmatrix}  &= \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\[4pt] 0 \end{bmatrix} \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  This leads to two linear equations in $x$ and $y$, which will yield the same values:

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  0.3x + 0.3y &= 0 \tag*{(1)} \\[6pt]
  0.2x + 0.2y &= 0 \tag*{(2)}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Using equation $(1)$, we find that $x=1$ and $y=-1$ is a solution.

  $$
  \begin{aligned}			
  \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}	
  \end{aligned}
  $$

  Therefore our first eigenvector is $\answer{\bm{p}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}}$ associated with $\lambda_1=0.5$.

  $$
  \begin{aligned}			
  \tag*{\textbf{A1}}	
  \end{aligned}
  $$

  For $\lambda_2=1$, we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \begin{bmatrix} -0.2 & 0.3 \\[4pt] 0.2 & -0.3 \end{bmatrix} \,\times \, \begin{bmatrix} x \\[4pt] y \end{bmatrix}  &= \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\[4pt] 0 \end{bmatrix}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  This leads to two linear equations in $x$ and $y$, which will yield the same values:

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  -0.2x + 0.3y &= 0 \tag*{(3)} \\[6pt]
  0.2x - 0.3y &= 0 \tag*{(4)}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Using equation $(3)$, we find that $x=3$ and $y=2$ is a solution.

  $$
  \begin{aligned}			
  \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}	
  \end{aligned}
  $$

  Therefore our second eigenvector is $\answer{\bm{p}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}}$ associated with $\lambda_2=1$.

  $$
  \begin{aligned}			
  \tag*{\textbf{A1}}	
  \end{aligned}
  $$

- The matrix $\bm{P}$ will be a matrix of the eigenvectors (written in the order $\bm{p}_1,\bm{p}_2$), and the matrix $\bm{D}$ will be a diagonal matrix with the eigenvalues on the diagonal (written in the order $\lambda_1,\lambda_2$).
  We have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &\tcbhighmath{\bm{T}^n = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 \\[4pt] -1 & 2 \end{bmatrix} \, \begin{bmatrix} 0.5 & 0 \\[4pt] 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}^n \, \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 \\[4pt] -1 & 2 \end{bmatrix}^{-1}} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- The long term behaviour will be determined by the matrix $\bm{T}^n$ as $n \to \infty$.
  For a diagonal matrix, we can note that this is a special case where if the matrix is raised to a power, each element can individually be raised to that power. Thus,

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \bm{D}^n &= \begin{bmatrix} 0.5^n & 0^n \\[4pt] 0^n & 1^n \end{bmatrix}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence as $n \to \infty$, we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
   \displaystyle\lim_{n \to \infty} \bm{D}^n &= \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0 \\[4pt] 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Our calculation will be

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \displaystyle\lim_{n \to \infty} \bm{T}^n &= \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 \\[4pt] -1 & 2 \end{bmatrix} \, \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0 \\[4pt] 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \, \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 \\[4pt] -1 & 2 \end{bmatrix}^{-1} \, \begin{bmatrix} 30 \\ 210 \end{bmatrix} \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[6pt]
  &= \begin{bmatrix} 144 \\ 96 \end{bmatrix}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  $\answer{\text{Long term, there will be $144$ chickens in coop A, and $96$ in coop B.}}$

  $$
  \begin{aligned}			
  \tag*{\textbf{A1}}	
  \end{aligned}
  $$

