    \begin{bmatrix} \rule[-3mm]{0pt}{9mm}\,\dfrac{2}{3} - 1 & \dfrac{6}{13} \\ \dfrac{1}{3} & \dfrac{7}{13}-1 \,\rule[-3mm]{0pt}{9mm} \end{bmatrix} \bm{X}_2 &= \bm{0} \\[4pt]
    \begin{bmatrix} \rule[-3mm]{0pt}{9mm}-\dfrac{1}{3} & \,\,\,\,\,\dfrac{6}{13}\,\, \\[8pt] \,\,\,\,\,\,\dfrac{1}{3} & -\dfrac{6}{13}\, \rule[-3mm]{0pt}{9mm} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix} &= \bm{0}  \hspace{3em} \left[\text{by letting } \bm{X}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}\right] \\[4pt]
    \begin{bmatrix} \rule[-3mm]{0pt}{9mm} -\dfrac{1}{3}a + \dfrac{6}{13}b\\[10pt]  \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\dfrac{1}{3}a - \dfrac{6}{13}b\rule[-3mm]{0pt}{9mm}  \end{bmatrix}&= \bm{0} \\[6pt]
    \dfrac{a}{3} - \dfrac{6b}{13} &= 0 \\[6pt]
    \dfrac{a}{3} &= \dfrac{6b}{13}  \\[6pt]
    a &= \dfrac{18b}{13}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Hence we get $\tcbhighmath{\bm{X}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 18 \\  13 \end{bmatrix}} \hspace{4em} [\text{by choosing } b = 13]$

- Using the power formula for a matrix, we can write $\bm{T}^n=\bm{PD}^n\bm{P}^{-1}$.
  From  part (g) we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \bm{P} &= \begin{bmatrix} 
      -1  & 18  \\[10pt]
  \,\,\,\,\,1 & 13
  \end{bmatrix} \\[16pt]
  \bm{D} &= \begin{bmatrix} 
      \frac{8}{39}  & 0  \\[10pt]
  0 & 1
  \end{bmatrix}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  As $n \to \infty$, we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \bm{D}^n &\to \begin{bmatrix} 
      0  & 0  \\[10pt]
  0 & 1
  \end{bmatrix}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  And therefore

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \bm{T}^n &\to \begin{bmatrix} 
      -1  & 18  \\[10pt]
  \,\,\,\,\,1 & 13
  \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 
      0  & 0  \\[10pt]
  0 & 1
  \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 
      -1  & 18  \\[10pt]
  \,\,\,\,\,1 & 13
  \end{bmatrix}^{-1}\\[16pt]
  &\approx \begin{bmatrix} 
      0.5806  & 0.5806  \\[10pt]
  0.4194 & 0.4194
  \end{bmatrix}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  In the long-term, the probability of getting a question correct regardless of whether the previous question was correct or incorrect, is approximately $0.5806$ according to the transition model.
  From part (f) (ii) we have that the probability of getting a question correct given that the previous question was correct is $\frac{2}{3}$.
  Hence, after a long break from watching the show, the probability of Steve getting all five questions correct in the first episode he watches is given by

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \mathrm{P}(RRRRR) &= 0.5806 \times \bigg(\frac{2}{3}\bigg)^4 \\[8pt]
  &\approx 0.1147
  \end{align*}
  $$

  $11.47$% is very close to $10$%.
  Therefore, we can conclude that $\tcbhighmath{\mbox{Tony's statement is correct.}}$

